body: On CentOS, even cmake 3.16.5 doesn't work. Failed with ``` Run Build Command(s):/usr/bin/ninja-build cmTC_d4ffc && [1/2] Building CUDA object CMakeFiles/cmTC_d4ffc.dir/main.cu.o [2/2] Linking CUDA executable cmTC_d4ffc FAILED: cmTC_d4ffc : && /opt/rh/devtoolset-8/root/usr/bin/g++ CMakeFiles/cmTC_d4ffc.dir/main.cu.o -o cmTC_d4ffc -lcudadevrt -lcudart_static -L"/usr/local/cuda/targets/x86_64-linux/lib/stubs" -L"/usr/local/cuda/targets/x86_64-linux/lib" -lcudadevrt -lcudart && : /opt/rh/devtoolset-8/root/usr/libexec/gcc/x86_64-redhat-linux/8/ld: /usr/local/cuda/targets/x86_64-linux/lib/libcudart_static.a(libcudart_static.a.o): undefined reference to symbol 'dlclose@@GLIBC_2.2.5' //lib64/libdl.so.2: error adding symbols: DSO missing from command line collect2: error: ld returned 1 exit status ```

CMake 3.16.4 works for CentOS, there're a lot of CUDA related changes from 3.16.2 to 3.17.0.
I think most related entries are:

https://blog.kitware.com/cmake-3-16-5-available-for-download/
> Ninja: Do not use nvcc response files with non-nvcc tools

https://blog.kitware.com/cmake-3-17-0-available-for-download/
> The "CMAKE_CUDA_RUNTIME_LIBRARY" variable and "CUDA_RUNTIME_LIBRARY" target property were introduced to select the CUDA runtime library used when linking targets that use CUDA.

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/3bdb0b620aaf726a67049886fec44b623dbc85b2/cmake/CMakeLists.txt#L709-L714
> 
> With the newly introduced `CMAKE_CUDA_RUNTIME_LIBRARY`, this UB may not work anymore.
> 
> Also tested with 3.16.5, works fine.
> 
> **Urgency**
> 
> Build is blocked by this.
> 
> **System information**
> 
> * OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 18.04
> * ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
> * ONNX Runtime version: 1.2.0
> * Python version: 3.6
> * GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): CMake 3.17.0 + Ninja + gcc 8.3.0
> * CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.2.89

yes, there's a problem starting with cmake 3.17 

To make the build succeed, 
replace the following line in onnxruntime/cmake/CMakeLists.txt
string(APPEND CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS "-cudart shared")
with
set(CMAKE_CUDA_RUNTIME_LIBRARY Shared)
and the CUDA compiler check should succeed.

> 
> yes, there's a problem starting with cmake 3.17
> 
> To make the build succeed,
> replace the following line in onnxruntime/cmake/CMakeLists.txt
> string(APPEND CMAKE_CUDA_FLAGS "-cudart shared")
> with
> set(CMAKE_CUDA_RUNTIME_LIBRARY Shared)
> and the CUDA compiler check should succeed.

we will try to get this fix checked in.

body:
> @jywu-msft Could you check CMake 3.16.5? That also failed on CentOS 7.
> (Well this is not urgent for me since I prefer the latest, but could we problematic for others.)
> 
> Also, would be nice if it can be cherry-picked to release versions.

CMAKE_CUDA_RUNTIME_LIBRARY was added in https://gitlab.kitware.com/cmake/cmake/-/commit/1f9321c68399c8cc37a2cb9c78ef45949412bd7b

It doesn't exist in cmake 3.16.5
e.g.
https://gitlab.kitware.com/cmake/cmake/-/blob/v3.16.5/Modules/Compiler/NVIDIA-CUDA.cmake

So it must be a different issue.

Verified that CentOS 7 + CMake 3.17 + Ort master works.
So that may caused by the same issue.

Maybe there's a gap where Ort's hack doesn't work but the official way hasn't come?
